properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: First accumulating snowfall of the season expected for many areas. Total snowfall: near 5 cm, with higher amounts over elevated terrain. Locations: central, western and northern Newfoundland. Time span: tonight through Tuesday. Remarks: A rain and snow mix over western Newfoundland will change to snow and spread into central and northern parts of the island through the night. The snow will change to rain over most areas by midday on Tuesday, but may persist through Tuesday afternoon and evening over parts of the Northern and Baie Verte Peninsulas, especially over higher terrain. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate. Motorists should be prepared for winter driving conditions. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2020-10-27T17:03:22-00:00

properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. Snow squalls have developed and are impacting Coral Harbour this morning. Bands of intense, heavy accumulating snow are expected to last throughout the day. Conditions will begin to improve this evening through the overnight. In the heaviest snow squall bands, 15 to 25 cm of snow can be expected. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Snow squall warnings are issued when bands of snow form that produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A Pacific front has moved onto the central coast producing heavy rain. The front will stall over the region today through Thursday, giving long episode of heavy rain.. The rain will be heaviest today with over 50 mm rainfall amounts expected. Total rainfall amount will likely exceed 200 mm by Thursday afternoon, when the front will finally move to the south and out of the region. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
